A family church service will be held today for the late Major General (Retired) Sikhulile Simpson Nyathi in Harare from 10AM to 3PM at the familyâ€™s Mabelreign home. Home Affairs and Cultural Heritage director of finance Mr Exavier Chisoko said last night that the event was purely a family programme. The late Maj-Gen Nyathi will be buried at the National Heroes Acre on Monday. <img class="wp-image-616428 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-32-5.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-32-5.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-32-5-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> National Heroes Acre On Thursday this week, the national hero was given a rousing send-off at his rural homestead in Gwanda, where speakers praised him for his love for the country and community. The body returned to Harare from Gwanda on the same day and will lay in state at the Charles Gumbo Barracks until burial on Monday.  Maj-Gen Nyathi died on Sunday morning at Josiah Magama Tongogara Barracks Referral Hospital in Harare at the age of 61 and was declared a national hero. The late Maj-Gen Nyathi held key appointments in the army with regular promotion until reaching the highest levels. He was a Major in 1984, Lieutenant Colonel in 1990, Colonel in 1997, Brigadier General in 2010 and Major General in 2020. <img class="alignnone wp-image-616422 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-30-4.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-30-4.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/06/Untitled-30-4-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> He also attended Zimbabwe National Army courses and was decorated for his continued dedication, and selfless and exemplary service to the nation. Maj-Gen Nyathi is survived by his wife and three children.